The Oath-Crossing is the neutral glade in the Great Northern Forest's Northern Crown where Midgaard and Kowloon formalized charter coexistence.
It marks the moment when two expanding city-states with overlapping territorial claims chose negotiated boundary over armed contest.
The glade was selected as the meeting site because it was equidistant from both cities' northern patrol boundaries at the time and had no prior territorial claim by either.
The agreement signed at the Oath-Crossing established the Great Northern Forest as a shared-jurisdiction zone rather than a contested border territory.
The terms set mutual recognition of each city's existing route certifications, defined a joint arbitration process for new claims, and created a witness requirement for all future territorial agreements in the Forest zone.
The crossing site was marked with two boundary stones — one bearing Midgaard's charter seal, one bearing the Neon Covenant's mark — placed side by side rather than facing each other.
The placement was deliberate: the stones do not mark a border between two territories; they mark a shared commitment to a single process.
The Oath-Crossing is the foundational document for the Great Northern Forest's current governance framework, which treats the Forest as a managed shared resource rather than a divided territory.
Neither city fully honors the original terms in current practice: Midgaard extends charter registration into Forest zones beyond the original shared-jurisdiction area; Kowloon routes Black Ledger operations through Forest corridors without joint arbitration.
Both cities acknowledge the Oath-Crossing as valid precedent while disputing each other's application of it.
The glade itself is maintained by a joint stewardship compact that has never lapsed, even during periods of active territorial dispute.

flags MIDGAARD
---
Midgaard's registry treats the Oath-Crossing as the foundational document for its northern territorial authority: it established the principle that Midgaard's charter system applies to contested zones through negotiated extension rather than conquest.
The Charter Review Board maintains the Oath-Crossing text as a primary reference for Great Northern Forest jurisdiction cases.
The two boundary stones at the glade are considered official registry markers; their placement is documented in Midgaard's territorial survey records.
Midgaard's current application of the Oath-Crossing extends charter registration further into the Forest than the original terms specified.
The Continuity faction argues this extension is consistent with the spirit of the agreement: the Oath-Crossing committed both cities to resolving claims through Midgaard's charter system rather than force.
The Reckoning faction argues the extension violates the letter of the agreement: the joint arbitration requirement was specific, and Midgaard's unilateral extension bypasses it.
Kowloon has filed formal objections to the extension three times. Midgaard has responded each time that the extension is charter-compliant and does not require joint arbitration.
The dispute is open. The Oath-Crossing's arbitration requirement has never been successfully invoked because both parties dispute what it requires.
Midgaard's position: the Oath-Crossing is a living document whose application evolves with circumstances. Kowloon's position: it is a fixed commitment whose terms do not evolve unilaterally.

flags KOWLOON
---
Kowloon's Black Ledger records the Oath-Crossing as the foundational covenant for northern route operations — the agreement that made Great Northern Forest transit legally viable rather than perpetually contested.
The Neon Covenant's northern operations depend on the Oath-Crossing's joint jurisdiction framework: without it, every Forest route would require bilateral renegotiation.
Kowloon's current Forest operations include Black Ledger-classified activities that the Oath-Crossing's joint arbitration requirement would technically require disclosing to Midgaard.
The Neon Covenant's position: classified crisis-protocol operations are exempt from the Oath-Crossing's disclosure requirements, which were written for commercial territorial claims, not security operations.
Midgaard's counter: the Oath-Crossing's disclosure requirement is not limited by purpose; it covers all activity in the joint jurisdiction zone.
This dispute mirrors the Midgaard dispute but in reverse: Kowloon accuses Midgaard of overextending the Oath-Crossing's charter registration clause; Midgaard accuses Kowloon of underapplying the disclosure clause.
Neither city has invoked the Oath-Crossing's arbitration mechanism against the other. Both are aware that doing so would require adjudicating each other's violations simultaneously.
Kowloon's internal assessment: the Oath-Crossing is holding. Neither city wants to replace it with something worse. The disputes are managed rather than resolved.
The glade's joint stewardship compact is one of the few active cooperation agreements between Midgaard and Kowloon that has never been challenged. Both cities maintain it without comment.

