---
Rakuen holds the Oath-Crossing in its civic memory primarily as a precedent for inter-city coexistence agreements rather than as a directly relevant governance document.
The Garden Ledger's analysis: the Oath-Crossing worked because both Midgaard and Kowloon had more to gain from shared governance than from contested governance.
Rakuen's three annexation refusals from Midgaard are analyzed against the Oath-Crossing precedent: Midgaard offered absorption, not coexistence; the Oath-Crossing model would have been coexistence.
If Midgaard had offered Rakuen an Oath-Crossing equivalent — joint arbitration, mutual recognition, shared governance framework — Rakuen's response might have been different.
Midgaard offered registry absorption instead. Rakuen refused. The Garden Ledger notes: absorption is not the same as recognition.
Rakuen's disaster-recovery operations occasionally require coordination with both Midgaard and Kowloon in the Great Northern Forest zone.
Both cities have honored Rakuen's coordinating requests under the Oath-Crossing's shared-jurisdiction framework, treating Rakuen's crisis operations as a third party to the agreement rather than an external actor.
This treatment is not documented in the Oath-Crossing itself. It has been established by practice. Rakuen considers this the most encouraging precedent for eventual formal recognition of its regional role.

