Mafdet's interest in the Oath-Crossing is maritime-legal: it established that cities can create shared jurisdiction over contested territory through documented oath rather than through conquest or institutional succession.
The Shrine of the First Claw considers the Oath-Crossing an exemplary oath form: witnessed, documented, with specific obligations and a designated arbitration mechanism.
That the arbitration mechanism has never been successfully invoked does not, in the Shrine's view, invalidate the oath. An oath's value is not measured by the frequency of its enforcement.
The oath's value is measured by whether it changed the parties' behavior. The Oath-Crossing demonstrably ended active territorial competition between Midgaard and Kowloon.
That is the oath's function. By Shrine standards, it is working.
Mafdet's Claw Mark Registry includes a notation for Great Northern Forest-origin cargo: verified under Oath-Crossing joint jurisdiction framework.
This notation affects risk assessment for cargo from the Forest zone: joint jurisdiction means two attestation systems apply, which is either double verification or doubled complexity depending on the case.
Mafdet's Ledger Houses treat Oath-Crossing joint certification as equivalent to dual attestation under inland and maritime standards.
The parallel is not exact, but the functional logic is the same: two independent systems both certifying the same cargo produces higher commercial trust than either alone.

